<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-683-960  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 683 960.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  July 30 1990 v7 n30 p116(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DEC posts first-ever loss in struggle to fit in PC world. (DigitalEquipment Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brennan, Laura.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (earnings).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Topic:     MicrocomputersMarket EntryComputer industryLossesFinancial ReportStrategic PlanningFourth Quarter.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   DEC results for 4th qtr 1989 and 1990. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Digital Equipment Corp. (DEC) last week posted its first-ever loss as aresult of consolidation costs and incentives for employees to leave the33-year-old company.andM;Massachusetts and New Hampshire's largest private employer spent $400 millionin its fourth fiscal quarter on the restructuring costs, following a similar$150 million charge in the March quarter.andP;  Net income for the fourth quarterbefore the $400 million charge was $85.2 million, compared with $313.2million a year ago.andM;Also, about 3,000 DEC employees have accepted a plan announced early thisyear to trim the company's work force, according to Mark Steinkrauss,director of investor relations for DEC in Maynard, Mass.andP;  The company hopesthat 5,000 more employees will take advantage of the financial and medicalbenefits of the outplacement plan.andM;DEC's revenues per employee historically have lagged behind those of othermultiplatform computer vendors, according to John Jones, general partner ofMontgomery Securities in San Francisco.andP;  In the last fiscal year, DEC took in$104,400 per employee; Hewlett-Packard Co.'s revenues totaled $142,000 perperson, and IBM's revenues came to $175,000 per person.andM;Staff cuts alone won't pull DEC out of its revenues slide, predicted JohnLogan, vice president of the Aberdeen Group Inc., a consulting firm inBoston.andM;The minicomputer maker must integrate PCs in a client-server environment, hesaid.andP;  &quot;All DEC gives [users] now is an industrial-strength informationenvironment where PCs are dumb terminals or VAXes are expensive fileservers.&quot;andM;-- Laura Brennan</TEXT></DOC>